  "prompt": "How do I prevent iMovie for iPad from cropping the top and bottom off my video that was originally taken in portrait orientation?",
  "response": "iMovie for iPad can sometimes crop portrait videos to fit its default 16:9 aspect ratio. Here's how you can prevent this and keep your video in its original aspect ratio:\n\n**1. Use the \"Pinch to Zoom\" Adjustment:**\n\n   *   **Import your video into iMovie:** Open iMovie, create a new project, and import your portrait video.\n   *   **Select the clip in the timeline:** Tap on the video clip you want to adjust.\n   *   **Pinch to Zoom/Scale:** You should see the clip displayed in the viewer above the timeline.  Use a *reverse* pinch gesture (pinch *outwards*) on the video in the viewer. This will zoom *out*, revealing more of the original video frame. Keep pinching outwards until you see black bars at the top and bottom of the video.  This means you've effectively zoomed out enough to display the full height of the portrait video without cropping.\n\n**2. Set Project Settings (if starting a new project):**\n\n   * **Start a New Movie:** Launch iMovie and tap the plus (+) button. Choose \"Movie\" to start a new project.\n   * **Choose \"Magic Movie\" or \"Storyboard\":** This step is important. Avoid creating a standard \"Movie\" project initially. Magic Movie and Storyboard projects allow you to set the aspect ratio before adding clips.\n   * **Add Your Clips:** Once the Magic Movie is created, you can import or add your portrait videos to the project. iMovie might still try to adjust, but you'll have more control later.\n\n**3. Editing in a Different App (if iMovie is consistently problematic):**\n\n   *   If iMovie consistently crops your video despite the pinch-to-zoom method, consider using another video editing app on your iPad. Popular alternatives include:\n      *   **LumaFusion:** A professional-grade video editing app (paid).\n      *   **InShot:** A more user-friendly app with free and paid options.\n      *   **CapCut:** A free video editing app by TikTok, known for its ease of use.\n   *   These apps generally offer more granular control over aspect ratios and allow you to force portrait mode without cropping.\n\n**Why iMovie Might Be Cropping:**\n\n*   **Default Aspect Ratio:** iMovie's default project settings are typically for a widescreen (16:9) aspect ratio. This is the standard for most video playback devices (TVs, computer monitors).\n*   **Automatic Adjustments:** iMovie tries to automatically adjust videos to fit the project's aspect ratio, which can lead to cropping when a video doesn't match the intended dimensions.\n\n**Troubleshooting Tips:**\n\n*   **Check iMovie Updates:** Ensure you have the latest version of iMovie installed from the App Store. Updates often include bug fixes and improvements.\n*   **Restart iMovie:** Sometimes, simply closing and reopening iMovie can resolve unexpected behavior.\n*   **Restart Your iPad:** A full device restart can clear temporary glitches.\n*   **Test with a Short Clip:** Try importing a very short portrait video clip to test if the problem persists. This helps isolate whether the issue is specific to a particular video file.\n\nBy using the pinch-to-zoom method or switching to a video editor that gives you finer control over aspect ratios, you should be able to successfully preserve the original portrait orientation of your videos in iMovie (or an alternative app) without unwanted cropping. Remember to experiment and find the method that works best for your specific workflow!\n",
